 Gaelic <i>Mac Giolla Chríosd</i>, <i>Mac Gille Chríosd</i> ‘son of the servant of Christ’."],"variants":[{"name":"Kilcrease","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Gilchrist  .","History: Robert Kilcrease (<i>c.</i> 1750–1808) came from Scotland(probably Kilmarnock) to Edgefield, SC, <i>c.</i> 1770."]},{"name":"Gilchrest","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Gilchrist  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Gilkerson","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <i>Mac Giolla Chrìosd</i> ‘son of <i>Gille Chrìosd</i>' (see   Gilchrist  )."]},{"name":"Gilkey","meanings":["Irish (northern): possibly a pet form of the Scottishpersonal name   Gilchrist  ."]},{"name":"Gilcrest","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Gilchrist  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Gilcrease","meanings":["Probably an altered form of Scottish   Gilchrist  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Mac","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   Maria   and   Margit  , now also used as an independent given name and as an element of compound names such as <i>Mai-Britt</i>, <i>Mai-Lis</i>, <i>Anne-Mai</i>, and <i>Britt-Mai</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Eruni","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Carlo, Ugo, Domenic, Francesco, Gino, Luigi, Santo, Vittorio, Aldo, Amadeo, Antonio.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of   Bruno  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bruno","meanings":["From the Germanic word <i>brun</i> ‘brown’. This was in use as a name in many of the ruling families of Germany during the Middle Ages. It was borne by a 10th-century saint, son of the  Emperor Henry  the Fowler, and by the Saxon duke who gave his name to Brunswick (German <i>Braunschweig</i>, i.e. ‘Bruno's settlement’). Its use in the English-speaking world, which dates from the end of the 19th century, may have been partly influenced by  Lewis Carroll's  Sylvie and Bruno (  1889 ), but more probably it was first used by settlers of German ancestry in the United States."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Mac Eruni Gilchrist was born in 1137, in Kincardineshire, Scotland, his father, Eruni Dunegal Gilchrist, was 30 and his mother, Beatrice Guilchriste, was 30. He had at least 1 daughter with Elizabeth of Menteith. He died in 1211, in Forfar, Forfarshire, Scotland, at the age of 74."},"et":{"1137–1211":"1137–1211","1137–Male":"1137–Surnud","1135–Female":"1135–Surnud","1151–1178":"1151–1178","1107–1145":"1107–1145","1107–Female":"1107–Surnud","1107":"1107","1137":"1137","1135":"1135","1145":"1145","1178":"1178","1211":"1211","1151":"1151","Kincardineshire, Scotland":"Kincardineshire, Scotland","Menteith, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Forfar, Forfarshire, Scotland":"Forfar, Forfarshire, Scotland","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1137–1